WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.640
It is an absolute trip to be here at RStudio conference talking to all of you about the

00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:20.000
R4DataScience online learning community, sharing a little bit about my personal story, and

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.799
then talking about diversity, equity, and inclusion in data science.

00:00:24.799 --> 00:00:28.639
And that's a lot to cover in the next 15-20 minutes, but we can do it.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:33.360
The reason this is so kind of wild to be here is that this is not something that kids like

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:35.439
me traditionally grow up and do.

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:41.040
I grew up to a poor working-class family outside of Buffalo, New York.

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:47.360
I am the first and only person in my family to both go to and graduate from college.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
I really liked college so much that I ended up going to graduate school twice.

00:00:52.560 --> 00:01:02.240
I did college at the education-at-any-cost model.

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:07.199
To give you some perspective, I graduated from high school in 1999, but I took eight

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:12.639
years to finish my undergrad, which means I graduated into the recession of 2008.

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:15.120
There were lots of jobs for people with degrees.

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:17.919
I have a ton of student loans.

00:01:17.919 --> 00:01:19.839
I went through a variety of careers.

00:01:19.839 --> 00:01:25.839
I did academia for a little while, and I ultimately ended up teaching high school science,

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:27.040
and I loved it.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:29.199
But I'm not sure if you know this.

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:31.040
Teaching doesn't pay the bills.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:33.760
It is an amazing career.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:38.080
I recommend it for everybody, but if you are carrying six figures worth of student loan

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:42.320
debt, teaching is probably not going to help you make ends meet.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:49.120
So I was in this position in about 2014 where I was evaluating my life, and I knew a couple

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:50.080
of things.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.160
One, I really liked video games.

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:56.080
And to be very specific, I really liked World of Warcraft.

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:00.879
And to be even more specific in the spirit of vulnerability, I could play World of Warcraft

00:02:00.879 --> 00:02:03.120
for like 12 to 15 hours a day.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:08.000
So there are some things going on in my life, but I really liked video games.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.080
I really liked video games, and data science was becoming a thing.

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:18.720
And it didn't seem like a fad, but data science was like, okay, I have some background that

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:22.399
could maybe put me in a position where I could do data science, and guess what?

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:26.399
I don't think I need to go back to school to become a data scientist.

00:02:26.399 --> 00:02:31.679
So I think that maybe I could do this thing, I could be a data scientist, and I could change

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:33.039
my financial future.

00:02:33.919 --> 00:02:40.399
So through a variety of kind of weird coincidences and situations, I found myself interviewing

00:02:40.399 --> 00:02:46.160
for this nebulously defined data-ish position with an esports startup based out of Dallas,

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.000
Texas, called PVP Live.

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:53.679
And to this day, I don't know where I got the courage to tell them I was a data scientist.

00:02:55.759 --> 00:02:56.800
I don't.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:01.839
I was registered in the Johns Hopkins Data Science Specialization from Coursera, but

00:03:01.839 --> 00:03:03.119
I took none of the classes.

00:03:03.839 --> 00:03:05.520
Like most of you here, I'm sure.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:13.119
And I had taken a graduate-level statistics course for one semester, and I knew a little

00:03:13.119 --> 00:03:14.720
bit about this language called R.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:19.520
But the fact remained that I knew more about data science than anybody at the company,

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:23.279
so nobody knew that maybe I wasn't a data scientist.

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:25.919
So I said, I'm a data scientist, and they hired me.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:31.360
So I worked remotely for a while, and then they told me to move to Dallas or find a new

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:32.559
job, so I moved to Dallas.

00:03:33.679 --> 00:03:37.119
And my first day on the job, they were like, congratulations, you're a manager.

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:40.080
And I was like, cool, maybe I don't even need to learn data science.

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:42.720
I'll just manage data scientists.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:44.160
So that was really cool.

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:49.360
And then six months on the job, I'm spending more and more of my time managing data scientists

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:51.520
and helping them learn data science.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.520
And I'm learning a little bit as I go, but really, I'm learning a lot about managing

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:59.759
and being at a startup, and this is six months in the job, and it's new, and it's exciting.

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:00.880
And this is kind of amazing.

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.960
I told this company I was a data scientist, and they hired me as a data scientist, and

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:07.679
then they promoted me as a manager of data scientists.

00:04:07.679 --> 00:04:09.360
I was like, this is so easy.

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:12.479
Like, you just tell people you're a data scientist, and they hire you.

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:18.000
So 12 months into the job, without warning and without notice, they let us go without

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:18.320
pay.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:23.519
And that is something of a misnomer, because they told me I could have equity.

00:04:23.519 --> 00:04:27.279
But if your company makes zero revenue, your equity is still zero.

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:31.200
Like, I knew enough math to know that this was not going to work out in my favor.

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:33.679
So I'm in Dallas.

00:04:33.679 --> 00:04:34.959
I've renewed my lease.

00:04:34.959 --> 00:04:39.920
I've gambled everything on data science and this esports startup, and I've kind of lost.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:41.279
So what do I do?

00:04:41.839 --> 00:04:43.359
Do I go back to teaching?

00:04:43.359 --> 00:04:46.160
I know teaching is not going to pay the bills, but I know I love it.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.959
But then I've got to get certified in Texas, and that's a process.

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:53.279
Or do I try to find something data-related or data-adjacent?

00:04:53.279 --> 00:04:57.359
And I decided to see what I could do with data, and maybe let go of the data scientist

00:04:57.359 --> 00:04:58.000
title.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.480
Does it matter if I'm called a data scientist, or does it matter if I'm working with data?

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:04.640
And I was like, well, I guess it matters that I'm working with data.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.239
But this time, I'm going to work for a company that I believe in.

00:05:08.239 --> 00:05:10.480
I did believe in the esports startup for a while.

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:13.519
But I was like, I need someone with a little more clout.

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:18.000
So I ended up working for the Girl Scouts of Northeast Texas, and ultimately at Teaching

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.440
Trust, which is where I am now.

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:25.040
And I do strongly recommend working for nonprofits to kind of start getting your feet wet with

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:26.480
data-related careers.

00:05:27.119 --> 00:05:28.559
I've had all sorts of titles.

00:05:28.559 --> 00:05:29.440
I've been an analyst.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:30.959
I've been in research and evaluation.

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:32.000
I've been in outcomes.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.640
And as long as you let go of that data scientist title, I think that you can get started with

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:38.880
data science just about anywhere.

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:44.559
So I was in this position where I'm working in nonprofits, and I'm doing analytical work,

00:05:44.559 --> 00:05:45.839
but I'm moving into management.

00:05:45.839 --> 00:05:50.160
It turns out once you're a manager, it's hard to not be a manager ever again, because people

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:52.399
are like, oh, no, we just want you to manage.

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.480
So I'm here, and I'm leveling up on the side.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:59.200
And I'm like, I want to get better at R. I kind of know this language.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:00.239
I think it's really useful.

00:06:00.239 --> 00:06:02.399
I think it can make a lot of what I do at work better.

00:06:03.119 --> 00:06:08.079
So as an educator, I was like, I'm going to teach myself R. I'm going to get better at

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:11.760
this, but I'm going to be transparent about my process, and I'm going to share that process

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:13.040
with other people.

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:17.600
So I took to social media and Twitter, and I was tweeting about things, and I was writing

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:18.239
blog posts.

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:22.480
And my first blog posts were helping people navigate that gap between using your computer

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:25.839
for Netflix and using your computer to do data science.

00:06:26.399 --> 00:06:30.640
And forget the gap between Excel and R. The gap between using your computer for Netflix

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:34.559
and the gap between navigating RStudio is very, very real.

00:06:34.559 --> 00:06:36.720
And people need those resources.

00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:39.920
So as I was doing this, two things happen.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.239
Someone on Twitter was like, there's this really good book called R for Data Science,

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:44.799
and it's free.

00:06:44.799 --> 00:06:46.079
And I was like, oh, cool.

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:47.040
I will read the book.

00:06:48.079 --> 00:06:50.239
But then Hadley retweeted me.

00:06:50.239 --> 00:06:52.799
And this is the most popular I've ever been on Twitter.

00:06:52.799 --> 00:06:56.559
It's probably the most popular I will ever be on Twitter, and that's OK.

00:06:56.559 --> 00:07:00.480
But I was benefiting from something that, for some people, we informally refer to as

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:02.640
the Hadley bump, right?

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:05.359
For 15 minutes, this is my 15 minutes of fame, right?

00:07:05.359 --> 00:07:08.720
And I'm like, I can take this and run with it, or I can forget about it.

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:12.399
People are interested in what I have to say for a limited amount of time.

00:07:12.399 --> 00:07:16.959
So I have the opportunity to take this book that I'm going to read anyway, and why not

00:07:16.959 --> 00:07:18.720
invite other people to read it with me?

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:24.880
So that was how the R for Data Science online learning community, the concept, started.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:29.760
But when Hadley retweets you, you have a limited amount of time to get people still interested

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:30.799
in what you're saying, right?

00:07:30.799 --> 00:07:33.760
I can't wait two weeks and come back and be like, hey, I have this cool idea.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:34.480
You have to move.

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:39.119
So it's all about finding your opportunities, people.

00:07:39.119 --> 00:07:40.799
So I have to come up with this plan.

00:07:40.799 --> 00:07:44.320
And my idea is like, well, I don't want to spend any money on this, and I don't want

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:46.799
anybody else to have to spend any money on this.

00:07:46.799 --> 00:07:50.079
We shouldn't have to spend money to learn how to do data science.

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:52.399
We're repurposing things we already know how to do.

00:07:53.119 --> 00:07:54.880
So it's like, it's going to be free.

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:57.279
It's going to be open to whoever wants to be a part of it.

00:07:57.279 --> 00:08:02.320
And so the original idea was, let's create a Slack group, and let's follow this curriculum

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:05.920
map that goes through maybe two chapters of the textbook every week.

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:07.839
And we'll finish in three to four months.

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:09.760
And we'll all be data scientists at the end.

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:10.399
We'll be pros.

00:08:10.399 --> 00:08:11.519
We'll be total experts.

00:08:11.519 --> 00:08:12.720
It's going to be amazing.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:17.119
And one thing we did with this group that I think is different from some other online

00:08:17.119 --> 00:08:22.320
learning communities is that we made it very clear that you had to be nice to people.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:24.320
And you would be kicked out if you weren't nice.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:29.600
This was going to be the kind of place where you could come, and you could say, I only

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:33.679
have two panes in our studio, and I know I'm supposed to have four, and I don't know

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:34.239
what to do.

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:38.960
And instead of someone being like, loser, you're so new at this, people would be like,

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:40.080
hey, you know what?

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:44.239
I can help you with that, and I'm going to stick with you until we figure that out.

00:08:44.239 --> 00:08:47.760
And so that was the idea for the kind of people you were going to encounter.

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:51.760
And then last week, we had this idea of there being mentors and learners.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:53.280
So you self-identified.

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:57.679
Am I here to mentor other people in their learning journey, or am I here to learn?

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:01.679
And maybe you were a learner for the first three chapters, and then you became a mentor

00:09:01.679 --> 00:09:02.400
for other things.

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:04.400
So it was this very fluid definition.

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:08.400
We weren't going to say, oh, we've done this survey, and you are a mentor, and you are

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:09.119
a learner.

00:09:09.119 --> 00:09:10.400
You got to identify.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:13.359
You got to take responsibility for your role in the community.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.719
So expectations versus reality.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:20.400
I could go on about it.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:22.159
I've got three hours of material on this.

00:09:22.159 --> 00:09:23.280
I will keep it brief.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:25.359
Essentially, I was like, no one's going to want to do this with me.

00:09:25.359 --> 00:09:26.479
This is an awful idea.

00:09:26.479 --> 00:09:28.000
But why not try?

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.599
I figured at the end of two weeks, I'd be begging my friends to do this with me.

00:09:31.599 --> 00:09:36.000
There'd be 12 of us, maybe 25, maybe 50 in this online learning community.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:36.880
And I'm like, that's fine.

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:37.520
That's fine.

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:38.080
That's fine.

00:09:39.119 --> 00:09:45.039
At the end of two weeks, when the invites went out, we had over 600 members, which for

00:09:45.039 --> 00:09:47.520
me meant that I'm not there as a learner anymore.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:49.200
I'm there as a community manager.

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:52.400
And that was a surprise.

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:54.320
That was something I wasn't expecting.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:58.640
But as we moved into things and I started thinking about what worked and what didn't

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:01.119
work, there was a lot.

00:10:01.119 --> 00:10:06.880
But I would say of the 600 people, within the first two weeks, we lost half of our members.

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:10.239
And we lost our members for one of two reasons.

00:10:10.239 --> 00:10:12.559
One, Slack was overwhelming.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:16.239
Most of us probably use Slack and are like, oh, I'm so tired of this tool.

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:16.880
It's amazing.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:18.239
But stop sending me stuff.

00:10:18.239 --> 00:10:19.760
But you know how to navigate it.

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:22.159
Not everybody knows how to navigate Slack.

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:24.559
Not everybody knows how to turn their notifications off.

00:10:24.559 --> 00:10:28.479
And when you log in and all of a sudden there's 450 messages, you're done.

00:10:28.479 --> 00:10:29.200
You are out.

00:10:30.159 --> 00:10:35.359
But we also had people who couldn't install or navigate R in RStudio.

00:10:35.359 --> 00:10:39.359
And that's where we lost 50% of our members was because we couldn't help them get over

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:39.919
those hurdles.

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:43.599
And we didn't even think of those as necessarily being the first hurdles.

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:47.679
So again, this gap from your computer for Netflix to your computer for data science

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:48.960
is very, very real.

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:53.520
There was also a misalignment and probably some miscommunication on my part about what

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:54.400
we were doing.

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:58.080
So some of the biggest things was people showed up and they were like, what time do classes

00:10:58.080 --> 00:10:58.719
start?

00:10:58.719 --> 00:10:59.760
I was like, they don't.

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:02.239
We're just going to read the book together.

00:11:02.239 --> 00:11:03.280
And like, you're on your own.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:05.679
And I'm not going to tell you when to do things or how to do things.

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:07.280
So that was a big thing.

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:08.880
We had people who were like, what book?

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:09.840
Like, what is the book?

00:11:10.719 --> 00:11:12.960
So that was a little bit lost in translation.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:17.280
And then another thing was that not everybody was tidy versus aligned.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:21.200
Now, listen, if you're having trouble installing R and RStudio on your computer, I don't expect

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:23.679
you to know the difference between base R and the tidyverse.

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:27.840
But if you're not there to help people learn the tidyverse, which is kind of a central

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:31.919
organizing principle of the book, it's going to be some rough sledding.

00:11:31.919 --> 00:11:33.440
So there was a lot to work out.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:35.919
And I didn't provide any training for mentors.

00:11:35.919 --> 00:11:37.760
I was like, yeah, you know how to be a mentor.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:41.359
Forget the fact that we send teachers to school to be certified in teaching.

00:11:41.359 --> 00:11:42.400
I was like, you're fine.

00:11:42.400 --> 00:11:43.200
Just be nice.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:43.840
It'll be good.

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:44.719
It'll all work out.

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:48.080
So at the end of round one, I was exhausted.

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:52.880
This was like, I just want to say people are like, data science is so hard.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:57.039
If you want a hard job, go be a community manager, because that is exhausting.

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:00.799
I, like, if you know a community manager in your life, give them a hug.

00:12:00.799 --> 00:12:01.840
Thank them for what they do.

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:03.440
That is a thankless career.

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:05.039
And it is incredibly difficult.

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:07.760
So there is, this happened, right?

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:09.359
And I was exhausted.

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:10.559
I didn't read the book.

00:12:10.559 --> 00:12:11.679
I hadn't finished the book.

00:12:12.559 --> 00:12:17.280
I was spending all of my time answering Twitter DMs, creating content, answering Slack messages,

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:18.719
helping connect people.

00:12:18.719 --> 00:12:21.280
So I had really moved into a community manager role.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:23.200
And it wasn't quite what I expected.

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:28.559
I will say that we did have one person who copped to finishing the entire curriculum.

00:12:29.359 --> 00:12:33.840
The guys at Hopkins tell me that is well within the margin of error and that I should be very,

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:35.359
very proud of that one person.

00:12:35.359 --> 00:12:35.840
And I am.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:39.919
I'm also proud of myself for doing something before I was ready.

00:12:39.919 --> 00:12:43.679
And I'm really, really proud of the people who are like, yeah, this is a crazy idea,

00:12:43.679 --> 00:12:44.799
but I'm going to do it.

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:49.359
Like, everybody who came along on that first adventure, I am incredibly proud of for taking

00:12:49.359 --> 00:12:51.039
a risk and trying something new.

00:12:51.599 --> 00:12:53.359
So then people are like, hey, when's round two?

00:12:55.280 --> 00:12:59.039
So in round two, I was like, I can't do this by myself.

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:00.159
Something needs to change.

00:13:00.159 --> 00:13:03.280
And I said, what do you all want to see in this community?

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:05.919
And people came back with all sorts of ideas.

00:13:05.919 --> 00:13:10.559
And when they said, I really want to see this, I said, that is a fantastic idea.

00:13:10.559 --> 00:13:13.200
How can I support you in making that a reality?

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:17.679
And what that did is it resulted in people being like, oh, no, I don't want to do the thing.

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:19.440
And okay, that's great.

00:13:19.440 --> 00:13:20.320
Then it's not going to get done.

00:13:20.320 --> 00:13:25.280
But it also resulted in people saying, well, I need you to help me to research software.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:26.719
Or I need you to retweet something.

00:13:26.719 --> 00:13:30.960
Or I need you to just kind of like help me talk in the group and recruit people for this.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:32.400
And those were things that I could do.

00:13:33.359 --> 00:13:36.400
So in round two, we had a lot of amazing things happen.

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:40.320
We had commitments to office hours, where people would give up an hour of their week

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:42.000
and just show up and answer questions.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:42.799
We did GitHub.

00:13:42.799 --> 00:13:44.400
We did the chapters out of the book.

00:13:45.119 --> 00:13:49.039
We had YouTube tutorial videos that community members made.

00:13:49.039 --> 00:13:53.440
And then three things that you're probably most familiar with is we have a website,

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:56.400
we have a Twitter account, and we have Tidy Tuesday.

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:57.919
These are not things that I built.

00:13:58.479 --> 00:14:02.640
I made sure everybody got in Slack and that everybody was happy and well behaved and nice

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:03.200
to each other.

00:14:03.200 --> 00:14:07.760
These are things that community members have built and that community members to this day

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:08.880
maintained.

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:13.679
If you want to get involved in this online learning community, you can go to that website

00:14:13.679 --> 00:14:14.880
and sign up.

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.039
And I strongly encourage you to do so.

00:14:18.159 --> 00:14:22.640
So when we're getting through round two, I'm realizing that the group isn't what I set out

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:23.760
to do, right?

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:29.760
We're not going through a text together and necessarily learning at a specific pace.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:33.840
But it's also an amazing community, and people are doing amazing things.

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:36.320
They're just not quite the things that I want to do.

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:42.559
So I am very excited to say that the group was handed off to a new set of leaders who

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:47.679
are enthusiastic and incredibly talented at what they do in keeping this group running.

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:53.119
And they are just, I think they were saying that there were over 2,500 members today,

00:14:53.119 --> 00:14:53.359
right?

00:14:53.359 --> 00:14:55.039
So the community continues to grow.

00:14:55.039 --> 00:14:56.320
It continues to be active.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:14:59.919
It continues to be a place where you can go and give and get help and R.

00:15:01.599 --> 00:15:06.400
So in my time away from the group, I started to think about a lot of things.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:11.840
And I thought a lot about my life and how data science has changed my life, right?

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:18.479
Just doing this community, just learning data science, just being a data scientist has changed

00:15:18.479 --> 00:15:19.119
my life.

00:15:19.119 --> 00:15:21.919
It's changed the people that I have access to.

00:15:21.919 --> 00:15:26.080
It has given me opportunities that I would never before have had in my life.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:29.039
And it has completely changed my socioeconomic status.

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:35.119
Instead of living in a financial crisis every single day of my life, I'm like two emergencies

00:15:35.119 --> 00:15:37.760
away from a financial crisis, right?

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:41.520
And that's a big deal when you grow up in poverty and you can't put food on the table,

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:42.960
like to have that security.

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:48.400
So I was like, if data science has done this for me, then it can do it for other people.

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:54.400
And it's my responsibility to help make it easier for other people move into data science.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:59.359
And I think we can all agree that data is used, data and data science is used every

00:15:59.359 --> 00:16:05.919
single day about, by, and for every single one of us to make choices and decisions for

00:16:05.919 --> 00:16:06.640
us.

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:10.960
Data is integral to our lives and it will be for the foreseeable future.

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:16.559
So as I started to look around data science as a whole, and I was like data science affects

00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:17.760
each and every one of us.

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:21.039
So each and every one of us deserves a seat at the table.

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:28.479
So what I'm asking people to do, there's like a laundry list of a million things I could

00:16:28.479 --> 00:16:33.200
ask you to do to start getting more people into data science and making it easier to

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:36.640
bring people into data science and removing some of the barriers.

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:38.400
But I'm only going to ask you to do one thing.

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:40.960
I'm going to ask you to be vulnerable.

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:43.919
I'm going to ask you to help me demystify data science.

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:49.840
Share publicly on Twitter, on your blog posts, in person, the things that you don't know.

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:54.479
Share the things that you're learning and share the mistakes that you've made.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.919
Data science isn't special.

00:16:57.919 --> 00:17:01.520
Data science isn't even necessarily a difficult career.

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:07.520
I think the more, there's no, there's no checklist for data science where we say, oh,

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:11.599
great, I have done every item on this list and then Hadley Wickham descends from the

00:17:11.599 --> 00:17:15.839
heavens and knights you a data scientist and everything, now you are free to practice

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:16.880
data science.

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:18.319
Go do data science.

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:24.079
And share with people, because what data science is, is it's about constantly learning and

00:17:24.079 --> 00:17:25.599
growing and taking risks.

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:30.560
I would argue that that is one of the defining characteristics of being in data science,

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:34.560
right, that you're constantly learning, you're constantly making mistakes, and you're

00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:36.560
constantly learning from mistakes.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:40.719
And the more that we normalize that and we say, hey, this is what us, the people who

00:17:40.719 --> 00:17:46.319
get paid to be data scientists, do, I think the more that we can start bringing in diverse

00:17:46.319 --> 00:17:50.959
voices and making data science as a community more equitable and inclusive.

00:17:52.479 --> 00:17:55.439
With that, I think I might be able to take one question.

00:17:56.239 --> 00:17:57.760
I don't know, Amina is my timekeeper.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:17:59.280
Okay.

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:11.520
Thank you.

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:13.760
Or you don't have any questions, and that's fine, too.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:15.599
You can always reach out to me on Twitter.

00:18:19.199 --> 00:18:20.319
Hi, thanks for your talk.

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:20.959
Yeah.

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:23.119
Thanks for being brave and vulnerable and all those things.

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:29.920
So when you stepped away from the community, who was it that took over and what was a part

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:30.640
of that decision?

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:31.920
Yeah.

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:33.439
So two of the people are in this room.

00:18:33.439 --> 00:18:38.319
One is a gentleman named Dennis, who is, I can't remember, I think he's in Kenya.

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:40.800
And then we have Thomas Mock in the back.

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:42.800
He has got Tidy Tuesday stickers.

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:44.000
I'm just putting that out there.

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:47.119
And then John Harmon, also over here on the end.

00:18:47.119 --> 00:18:50.400
So these are the gentlemen that are currently running the community and keeping it alive

00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:59.680
and making sure everything is going as planned.

